issue.title: Trufflerruby image with graalvm
issue.body:
Greetings.

When we launch the trufflerruby  with flags:
TRUFFLERUBYOPT='--vm.Xmx8G --vm.Xmn4G --jvm'

from the image:
ghcr.io/graalvm/truffleruby-community:debian

We receive the following error:
'--jvm' is only supported when this launcher is part of a GraalVM.


We are new to trufflerruby, so this error seems a bit unusual for the GraalVM packaged in the image.
Can someone tell us if we are downloading the wrong image or doing something wrong?
Thanks in advance.

issue.body:
Greetings.

When we launch the trufflerruby  with flags:
TRUFFLERUBYOPT='--vm.Xmx8G --vm.Xmn4G --jvm'

from the image:
ghcr.io/graalvm/truffleruby-community:debian

We receive the following error:
'--jvm' is only supported when this launcher is part of a GraalVM.


We are new to trufflerruby, so this error seems a bit unusual for the GraalVM packaged in the image.
Can someone tell us if we are downloading the wrong image or doing something wrong?
Thanks in advance.

comment.body:
This is expected, `ghcr.io/graalvm/truffleruby-community:debian` has always only contained the native truffleruby standalone, which supports only `--native` and not `--jvm` mode.

See this section of the README:
> Via Docker. For Native Standalone see [official release images](https://github.com/graalvm/container/blob/master/truffleruby-community/README.md) and [nightly images](https://github.com/flavorjones/truffleruby/pkgs/container/truffleruby). For JVM Standalone there are no Docker images yet, but you can easily [download it](https://github.com/oracle/truffleruby/blob/master/doc/user/installing-truffleruby.md) and take inspiration from the [Native Standalone Dockerfiles](https://github.com/flavorjones/truffleruby/blob/master/tool/dockerfiles/stable.dockerfile).

And https://github.com/oracle/truffleruby/blob/master/doc/user/installing-truffleruby.md#jvm-standalone

pull_request.title: [GSoC] Use a compact hash table for RubyHash instead of the buckets strategy
pull_request.body:
Hey guys !

This is my first working implementation of hash tables that love you :') https://blog.toit.io/hash-maps-that-dont-hate-you-1a96150b492a. TLDR : This is a representation strategy that efficiently (hopefully!) allows insertion-order preserving hash tables. It aims to replace the BucketHashStorage strategy.

@eregon encouraged me to write the PR this early for review and feedback, but it's still incomplete. In particular : 

1- Code still missing lots of profiles in if conditions and loops, I wanted to focus on getting it right first before making it fast

2- Code is sometimes duplicated by Ctrl-C/Ctrl-V in several methods

3- Didn't test it that heavily yet, so probably several bugs hiding here and there (but the interpreter executes the entire core without crashing so that's something)

4- I might be using the truffle framework in a stupid way or unaware of some patterns.

That said, let me know what you think. Also, I edited some misleading documentation in HashStoreLibrary.java. 

If you want to test, make sure the JVM running truffleruby has the -DBigHashStrategy=compact property set by any means.

PullRequest: truffleruby/4028
Update graal import.

Fix rb_type() for values >= 1**62 and < 1**63 and corresponding negative values

* So rb_type(value) == T_FIXNUM is equivalent to RB_FIXNUM_P().
* Fix related rb_big* functions so they handle such values (which are not RubyBignum objects).
RB_INT2FIX() is constexpr now that we use the original definition
Workaround grpc_c.so needing symbols from libz and libssl but not depending on them natively
CI: Print RbConfig::MAKEFILE_CONFIG on CRuby on all platforms
WIP: use the native toolchain

Adapt MRI C ext tests to load fine

* They would fail to e.g. `undefined symbol: rb_yield_block`

We need to use a wrapper to call the Init_* function too

* In case that raises an error.
* Also this calls Init_* with the cext lock, it was missing before.

Use the original definition of RB_SPECIAL_CONST_P()

* Otherwise RBIMPL_ATTR_CONST() RBIMPL_ATTR_CONSTEXPR(CXX11) cause errors.
* rb_tr_special_const_p() is slower when running extensions natively.

Revert "Use the original definition of RB_SPECIAL_CONST_P()"

This reverts commit d871e9f915e5b9a714990c5ddcac12a89cff402e.
Add a fast-path for RB_SPECIAL_CONST_P()

Fix return type for encoding_spec_rb_enc_raise()

* Fails with SPEC_CAPI_CXX=true.

Don't include warnflags in cxxflags

* Most of these warnflags only work for C and not C++.
* On CRuby cxxflags actually seems empty.
Fixes for C++
Run SPEC_CAPI_CXX=true C API specs in CI
Compile libtruffleposix and spawn-helper using the system compiler
CRuby headers need -fdeclspec on system clang on macOS Mojave

PullRequest: truffleruby/4037
[WIP] Update graal import

Run C extensions natively

* libtruffleruby.so is still run on Sulong to limit the changes needed.
* libtrufflerubytrampoline.so is a new library which declares C API functions in native and forwards to Sulong.
* st.c is copied to libtrufflerubytrampoline.so since it does not need to run on Sulong.
* Define TRUFFLERUBY_ABI_VERSION in headers directly for simplicity and reliability, trampoline.c and st.c need it but have no easy way to get the value from Ruby.
* Remove dependencies on polyglot.h in public extension headers, since that functionality is not available when not running on Sulong.

release.name: TruffleRuby - GraalVM Community 23.1.1
release.body:
TruffleRuby is a high-performance implementation of the Ruby programming language.
TruffleRuby aims to be fully compatible with the standard implementation of Ruby, MRI.
More information is available on the website: http://www.graalvm.org/ruby/
TruffleRuby comes in two standalone modes, native and jvm, for both Oracle GraalVM and Community Edition.
See [the documentation](https://github.com/oracle/truffleruby/blob/master/doc/user/installing-truffleruby.md) for which release asset corresponds to what.

### Changelog

- Build based on latest GraalVM JDK release (23.1.1)
